M|references|| Factor | Self-Implementation | EOS Implementer |
M|references||--------|-------------------|-----------------|
M|references|| **Cost** | Free (book + time) | $50K-$100K+ over 2 years |
M|references|| **Speed** | Slower (learning while doing) | Faster (experienced facilitator) |
M|references|| **Facilitation** | Integrator or Visionary facilitates (hard to participate and facilitate) | Neutral third party facilitates (leadership fully participates) |
M|references|| **Accountability** | Self-policed | External accountability partner |
M|references|| **Customization** | High flexibility (can adapt tools) | Purist approach (tools used as designed) |
M|references|| **Common for** | Bootstrapped companies, strong Integrators | Funded companies, teams with internal conflict |
M|references|| **Risk** | Higher (easy to skip hard parts) | Lower (Implementer pushes through resistance) |
M|references|- The leadership team has read *Traction* and is aligned on implementing EOS
M|references|- The Integrator is a strong facilitator who can run sessions
M|references|- Budget constraints make an Implementer impractical
M|references|- The company is smaller (under 20 people) and the dynamics are simpler
M|references|- The leadership team has unresolved conflict that requires a neutral party
M|references|- No one on the team is a strong enough facilitator
M|references|- Previous self-implementation attempts have stalled
M|references|- The company is growing fast and cannot afford a slow rollout
M|references|- The budget allows for the investment ($4K-$8K per ses, typically 10-12 sessions)
M|references|EOS only works if the entire leadership team is committed. Partial adoption creates more problems than it solves.
M|references|**Step 1: Share the book.** Give every leadership team member a copy of *Traction*. Ask them to read it within two weeks.
M|references|**Step 2: Discuss openly.** Schedule a 2-hour meeting to discuss:
M|references|- What resonated? What did not?
M|references|- What problems could EOS solve for us?
M|references|- What concerns or objections do people have?
M|references|**Step 3: Address objections honestly.**
M|references|| Common Objection | rsp |
M|references||-----------------|----------|
M|references|| "We don't have time for another meeting" | Level 10 replaces your existing meetings, not adds to them. Most companies cut total meeting time. |
M|references|| "This is too rigid" | The tools are simple and flexible. The discipline is what creates results. |
M|references|| "We've tried frameworks before" | EOS is not a flavor-of-the-month. It is a complete operating system adopted consistently for two years. |
M|references|| "I don't want to be told how to run my department" | EOS defines what to achieve, not how to achieve it. Your autonomy within your seat is preserved. |
M|references|| "Our business is different" | EOS works for every entrepreneurial company. Over 250,000 companies use it across every industry. |
M|references|**Step 4: Commitment vote.** After the discussion, ask each leader: "Are you in? Yes or no." Anything less than full commitment from the entire leadership team means EOS will struggle.
M|references|Once the leadership team has completed Focus Day, VB1, and VB2, it is time to share the vision with the entire company.
M|references|**Duration:** 90 minutes
M|references|**Attendees:** Everyone in the company
M|references|**Agenda:**
M|references|1. **What is EOS?** (10 min) Brief overview of the Six Key Components
M|references|2. **Our Core Values** (15 min) Share each value with behavioral indicators and examples
M|references|3. **Our Core Focus** (10 min) Purpose and niche
M|references|4. **Our V/TO** (20 min) Walk through the complete V/TO: 10-Year Target, 3-Year Picture, 1-Year Plan, Quarterly Rocks
M|references|5. **What Changes for You** (15 min) Level 10 meetings at every level, rocks for every team, scorecards for every department
M|references|6. **Q&A** (20 min) Open floor for questions
M|references|After the company-wide meeting, each department head runs a department-level ses:
M|references|- [ ] Share how the department supports the company rocks
M|references|- [ ] Set department-level rocks for the quarter
M|references|- [ ] Build a department-level Scorecard
M|references|- [ ] Schedule the department's weekly Level 10 meeting
M|references|- [ ] Answer team-specific questions
M|references|| Failure | Root Cause | Prevention |
M|references||---------|-----------|------------|
M|references|| **EOS fades after 3 months** | Leadership loses discipline when initial excitement wears off | Commit to the full 2-year journey. Schedule all sessions in advance. |
M|references|| **Level 10 meetings get cancelled** | "Too busy" becomes an excuse | Non-negotiable: the meeting happens every week, no exceptions. |
M|references|| **Visionary disengages** | Visionaries get bored with operational discipline | Define the Visionary's specific roles and keep them engaged in strategic IDS. |
M|references|| **Integrator overwhelmed** | Integrator tries to do everything | Delegate operational functions. The Integrator manages leaders, not tasks. |
M|references|| **Rocks are set but not tracked** | Weekly rv skipped or superficial | Track rocks in every Level 10. IDS off-track rocks immediately. |
M|references|| **People issues avoided** | Leadership avoids hard conversations | Use the People Analyzer as an objective tool. Set 90-day deadlines. |
M|references|| **Core values are ignored** | Values defined but not used in hiring, firing, or reviews | Reference values in every people dec. Fire someone who violates values (it sends a message). |
M|references|| **Partial adoption** | Some leaders do EOS, others do not | Full leadership team must be committed. No opt-outs. |
M|references|| **Overcomplication** | Adding extra tools, extra metrics, extra meetings | Keep it simple. EOS is powerful because it is simple. Resist the urge to add complexity. |
M|references|| **No cascading to departments** | EOS stays at the leadership level | Every department should have Level 10s, rocks, and scorecards within 6 months. |
M|references|Use this assessment quarterly to track your EOS implementation progress. Rate each item 1-5 (1 = not started, 5 = mastered).
M|references|Rate each item 1-5 (1 = not started, 5 = mastered). 30 items total across all six components.
M|references|| Component | Key Items to Rate |
M|references||-----------|------------------|
M|references|| **Vision** | V/TO complete, leadership aligned, shared with org, rv quarterly, filters all decisions |
M|references|| **People** | Accountability Chart defined, single owners, People Analyzer run, GWC assessed, tough decisions made in 90 days |
M|references|| **Data** | 5-15 weekly metrics, owners and goals set, rv in Level 10, off-track IDS'd, department scorecards exist |
M|references|| **Issues** | IDS used consistently, root cause focus, permanent solutions, both lists maintained, safe to raise issues |
M|references|| **Process** | 5-7 core processes identified, documented, trained and followed, compliance measured, rv quarterly |
M|references|| **Traction** | Rocks set and tracked, 80%+ completion, weekly Level 10s, meetings score 8+, to-do completion 90%+ |
M|references|**Scoring (out of 150):**
M|references|- **120-150:** EOS mastery. Fully embedded.
M|references|- **90-119:** Strong adoption. Close remaining gaps.
M|references|- **60-89:** Good progress. Focus on lowest-scoring areas.
M|references|- **30-59:** Early implementation. Stay the course.
M|references|- **Below 30:** Just starting. Commit to the two-year journey.